Howletts, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howlot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Hewlett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hewlett","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Somerset): variant of   Howlett  . This surname is also established in Ireland (mainly Tipperary)."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":23,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":96,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Peter Howlot was born about 1359, in Bacton, Suffolk, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Peter Howlot. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1359–":"umbes 1359–Surnud","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","1382–1456":"1382–1456","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1359":"1359","1456":"1456","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1382":"1382","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, England","Howletts, Kent, England":"Howletts, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1359–":"noin 1359–Kuollut","1357–Male":"1357–Kuollut","1382–1456":"1382–1456","1359–Female":"1359–Kuollut","1359":"1359","1456":"1456","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","about 1359":"noin 1359","1382":"1382","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, England","Howletts, Kent, England":"Howletts, Kent, England"},"fr":{"about 1359–":"environ 1359–Décédée","1357–Male":"1357–Décédé","1382–1456":"1382–1456","1359–Female":"1359–Décédée","1359":"1359","1456":"1456","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","about 1359":"environ 1359","1382":"1382","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, Angleterre","Howletts, Kent, England":"Howletts, Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Peter Howlot est née environ 1359, à Bacton, Suffolk, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Peter Howlot. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"about 1359–":"um 1359–Verstorben","1357–Male":"1357–Verstorben","1382–1456":"1382–1456","1359–Female":"1359–Verstorben","1359":"1359","1456":"1456","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","about 1359":"um 1359","1382":"1382","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, England","Howletts, Kent, England":"Howletts, Kent, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Peter Howlot wurde um 1359 in Bacton, Suffolk, England